erman   Dingel   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Dunkley","meanings":["English:","(Northamptonshire): habitational name from Dinckley in Lancashire, recorded as <i>Dunkythele</i> in 1246 and <i>Dinkedeley</i> in 1258, probably arising from an old British name, composed of elements meaning ‘fort’ + ‘wood’, with the addition of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","in the South Midlands perhaps a variant of   Dingley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":2,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":96,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":105,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Dingley was born in Charlton, Worcestershire, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Hardwick."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1472–1567":"1472–1567","–Male":"Surnud","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1455":"1455","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","Charlton, Worcestershire, England":"Charlton, Worcestershire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1472–1567":"1472–1567","–Male":"Kuollut","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1455":"1455","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","Charlton, Worcestershire, England":"Charlton, Worcestershire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1472–1567":"1472–1567","–Male":"Décédé","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1455":"1455","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","Charlton, Worcestershire, England":"Charlton, Worcestershire, Angleterre","London, Middlesex, England":"Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Dingley est né à Charlton, Worcestershire, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Alice Hardwick."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1472–1567":"1472–1567","–Male":"Verstorben","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1455":"1455","1472":"1472","154